UML:TaggedValue.value: A measure with a uom or a quantity (without a uom). This should not be used except in situations where the underlying class of data is captured elsewhere. For example, via a measure class.
The unit of measure for the quantity. This value must conform to the values allowed by a measure class. If the value is a measure then the uom must be specified.
The name of something within a naming system.
The naming system within the name is (hopefully) unique.
IADC bearing wear code: integer 0 - 8 or one of the letters E, F, N or X. .
A reference to a name in another node of the xml hierachy. This value represents a foreign key from one element to another.
A reference to the unique identifier (uid attribute) in the node referenced by the name value. This attribute is required within the context of a WITSML server.
A description related to the sequence number.

A measured depth coordinate in a wellbore. Positive moving from the reference datum toward the bottomhole. All coordinates with the same datum (and same uom) can be considered to be in the same Coordinate Reference System and are thus directly comparable.
The unit of measure of the quantity value.

A pointer to the reference datum for this coordinate value as defined in WellDatum. This value is assumed to match the uid value in a WellDatum. If not given then the default WellDatum must be assumed.
A reference to the unique identifier of another element. This value represents a foreign key from one element to another. The value should match the value of an attribute of type uidString.
A reference to the unique identifier (uid attribute) in the object referenced by the name value. This attribute is required within the context of a WITSML server.
A reference to the unique identifier (uid attribute) in the node referenced by the index value. This attribute is required within the context of a WITSML server.
A large positive integer (one based count or index) with a maximum value of 2,147,483,647 (4-bytes).
The distance to a one minute boundary on the east or west of a point. USA Public Land Survey System.
The unit of measure of the distance value.
Specifies the reference line that is the origin of the distance.
A reference to a index value in another node of the xml hierachy. This value represents a foreign key from one element to another.
A volume per volume measure that is constrained to a unit of percent.
A unitless quantity. This should not be confused with a dimensionless measure.
Defines a sequence number and with an optional description attribute.
A extension value. Each standard name should document the expected maximum size. Knowledge of the semantics must be provided with the context of the usage of this type.
The unit of measure for the value. This value must conform to the values allowed by a measure class.
Some combination of NE,NW,SW,SE,N2,S2,E2,W2,C,TRxx,LTnn. USA Public Land Survey System.

A unique identifier of an object parent. This should only be used for the uid of a parent object (i.e., a foreign key to another object). It should not be used for child nodes of an object. The value is not intended to convey any semantic content (e.g., it may be computer generated). The purpose of this type is to facilitate modifying the optionality of parentage uids in derived schemas.
A generic measure type. This should not be used except in situations where the underlying class of data is captured elsewhere. For example, for a log curve.
The unit of measure for the quantity.
A representation of a list of xsd:string values, restricted to strings without embedded whitespace.
A textual string that retains all whitespace.
A unit of measure acronym from the POSC unit of measure file.
The unit of measure for the quantity. If for some reason a uom is not appropriate for the quantity, a unit of "Euc" should be used.
A community assigned human recognizable name. This type of value is intended to be unique and is generally a candidate to be constrained to an enumerated list.
A unique (short) code associated with the name.
The name of something within a mandatory naming system with an optional code.
The naming system within the name is unique.

A reference to a wellDatum in the current well. This value must match the uid value in a WellDatum. This value represents a foreign key from one element to another. This is an exception to the convention that a foreign key must utilize both a human contextual name and a uid value. For messages outside the context of a server then this value will commonly match the value of the name of the wellDatum (e.g., 'KB') if uids are not not used in that context. This was a compromise in order to allow the coordinate structures to be simple and still be usable both within the context of a server and outside the context of a server.
A pointer to the reference datum for this coordinate value as defined in WellDatum. If not given then the default WellDatum must be assumed.
A pointer to the reference datum for this coordinate value as defined in WellDatum. If not given then the default WellDatum must be assumed.
Pump Action: 1 = Single acting, 2 = double acting.
A positive integer (one based count or index).
Indexes things with the same name. That is the first one, the second one, etc.

A date with a time of day and a mandatory time zone offset. This must captute the correct date-time relative to UTC. It is not necessary to use a local time zone because software may convert the date-time to a different local time zone (while retaining correct date-time relative to UTC). See acquisitionTmeZone in commonData for the original time zone of times in an object.
The date and time when this local time zone became active. This value must be defined on the second and subsequent occurrences.
A time zone conforming to the XSD:dateTime specification.
The distance to a one minute boundary on the north or south of a point. USA Public Land Survey System.
The unit of measure of the distance value.
Specifies the reference line that is the origin of the distance.

A local time zone conforming to the XSD:dateTime specification. The dTim attribute can capture when the local time zone changed. The use of this type is generally related to a specific (set of) date and time for which the original time zone needs to be captured.
A calendar year (CCYY) in the gregorian calendar. This type is meant to captute original invariant values. It is not intended to be used in "time math" where knowledge of the time zone is needed.
A single value. The encoding may utilize any of several xsd encodings. Something external to the value must define the encoding.

A vertical (gravity based) depth coordinate within the context of a well. Positive moving downward from the reference datum. All coordinates with the same datum (and same uom) can be considered to be in the same Coordinate Reference System and are thus directly comparable.
The unit of measure of the quantity value.
The name of something within a naming system.
The naming system within the name is (hopefully) unique.
A short textual description of something.
A locally unique identifier. The value is not intended to convey any semantic content (e.g., it may be computer generated).
An estimate wind strength based on the Beaufort Wind Scale. Values range from 0 (calm) to 12 (hurricane).
Sections are numbered "1" through "36." Irregular sections may be designated with a single value after a decimal point. USA Public Land Survey System.

A vertical (gravity based) elevation coordinate within the context of a well. Positive moving upward from the reference datum. All coordinates with the same datum (and same uom) can be considered to be in the same Coordinate Reference System and are thus directly comparable.
The unit of measure of the quantity value. If not given then the default unit of measure of the explicitly or implicitly given datum must be assumed.
The version of the schema. The first level is fixed. The fourth level can vary to represent on the constraints defined in enumerations and XML loader files.

The value of a name element in another data-object. The information in this type represents a foreign key to a data-object instance. Knowledge of the type of object being referenced is defined by an attribute.
The type of data-object being referenced (e.g., "well", "wellbore").

The name of a lithostratigraphy, with the "kind" attribute specifying the lithostratigraphic unit-hierarchy (Group, Formation, Member or Bed). The entry at each level is free text for the local lithostratigraphy at that level in the hierarchy. If a single hierarchy is defined, it is assumed this is at the Formation level in the hierarchy and kind=formation should be used for the entry.

Representation of a number as a double, possibly qualified as a ratio of doubles. Ratio component attributes 'numerator' and 'denominator' may be both present or both absent. When ratio component attributes are present, the ratio represented is to be used with the double representation included for human readability. A 'canonical' representation, according to the following rules, is suggested: Only use numerator/denominator when the representation of the number as double is not sufficiently precise (i. e. causes errors of accumulation). Express both numerator and denominator as integers (doubles with integer values) reduced to 'least common denominator' if possible.
The name of a chronostratigraphy, with the "kind" attribute specifying the chronostratigraphic unit-hierarchy (Era, Period, Epoch, Stage).
The angle of a Y axis from North. This is a variation of planeAngleMeasure with an attribute defining the direction of north.
The unit of measure of the azimuth value.
Specifies the direction to be considered North for the y axis.
A floating point value which is greater than zero and less than or equal to one.
A geodetic zone with values from 1 to 60 and a required direction of "N" (North) or "S" (South). For example, "21N".
A positive or negative count with a maximum positive value of 2147483647 (4-bytes).

A comment or remark intended for human consumption. There should be no assumption that semantics can be extracted from this field by a computer. Neither should there be an assumption that any two humans will interpret the information in the same way (i.e., it may not be interoperable).
A non-negative integer (zero based count or index) with a maximum value of 32767 (2-bytes). For items that represent "number of" something or a "sequential" count or index.
Designates a particular quarter of a township. USA Public Land Survey System.

A user assigned human recognizable contextual name of something. There should be no assumption that (interoperable) semantic information will be extracted from the name by a third party. This type of value is generally not guaranteed to be unique and is not a candidate to be replaced by an enumeration.
